1
00:01:38,832 --> 00:01:40,765
What the hell?

2
00:01:42,869 --> 00:01:45,070
The stagecoach is coming!

3
00:01:45,139 --> 00:01:47,739
The stagecoach is coming!

4
00:02:05,892 --> 00:02:08,327
No need to stop.

5
00:02:11,465 --> 00:02:15,166
Hyah!
Hyah! Hyah!

6
00:02:35,422 --> 00:02:37,422
Hands up!

7
00:02:39,960 --> 00:02:42,427
Howdy.

8
00:02:51,438 --> 00:02:54,372
This is the third time
this month.

9
00:02:54,441 --> 00:02:57,375
You really should give
the depositors a chance...

10
00:02:57,444 --> 00:02:59,410
To build up
their accounts.

11
00:02:59,479 --> 00:03:01,613
Huh?

12
00:03:05,385 --> 00:03:08,720
Good luck.
Hey. I've got a job.

13
00:03:08,789 --> 00:03:12,591
What'll it be?

14
00:03:12,659 --> 00:03:15,894
I would really
love a gin and tonic--

15
00:03:15,963 --> 00:03:18,262
slice of lime,
cracked ice.

16
00:03:22,235 --> 00:03:23,969
Whiskey.

17
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:26,137
Okay, belle.
Okay. All right.

18
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,139
Get out! Get out!

19
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:30,174
Lemme give you an I.O.U.

20
00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:32,711
I am done working
for I.O.U.S,

21
00:03:32,779 --> 00:03:35,880
and I'm done
working for rocks!

22
00:03:35,949 --> 00:03:38,783
Here...
Here's a refund.

23
00:03:38,852 --> 00:03:41,686
Ohhh...

24
00:03:44,424 --> 00:03:46,424
Zeke.

25
00:04:00,841 --> 00:04:03,975
Why,
Harry Bob Ferguson!

26
00:04:04,044 --> 00:04:07,846
Ahh!
What a terrific
surprise.

27
00:04:07,914 --> 00:04:09,848
I must confess,

28
00:04:09,916 --> 00:04:12,350
I've never
considered you to be...

29
00:04:12,418 --> 00:04:14,352
The reader type-- per se.

30
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:16,621
I need
a big damn book.

31
00:04:16,690 --> 00:04:20,424
A big damn book. Super.
We certainly have a few.

32
00:04:20,493 --> 00:04:24,729
But if I might, have you
been more in the market...

33
00:04:24,798 --> 00:04:27,632
For a coffee table,
impress-your-guests thing,

34
00:04:27,701 --> 00:04:32,370
or are you leaning towards
a flip-right-through-it-
before-bed number?

35
00:04:32,438 --> 00:04:34,572
Like a chocolate?

36
00:04:35,575 --> 00:04:37,508
Oh. Not another word.

37
00:04:37,577 --> 00:04:42,380
I'd like to recommend
one of my very favorite
authors to you--

38
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:44,615
woman named Jane Austen.

39
00:04:44,685 --> 00:04:48,703
This is a writer
of just wonderfully
exquisite prose.

40
00:04:48,772 --> 00:04:52,290
And as you see,
it's a big damn book.

41
00:04:52,359 --> 00:04:55,293
Ha ha ha!
Oh,pride and prejudice.

42
00:04:55,362 --> 00:05:00,131
You're going to get more
than a run for your money.

43
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:02,133
How much?

44
00:05:02,202 --> 00:05:06,204
Well, I think $2.00
is a fair price.

45
00:05:06,273 --> 00:05:08,740
Really?
Mm-hmm.

46
00:05:08,808 --> 00:05:11,910
How much for
just the pride?

47
00:05:11,979 --> 00:05:16,114
Well, actually,
one does hate
to break up the set.

48
00:05:17,817 --> 00:05:20,752
All right.
I got to test it first.

49
00:05:20,820 --> 00:05:23,255
I beg your pardon?
Aah!

50
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:25,290
Where is
your outhouse?

51
00:05:25,359 --> 00:05:27,292
It's in back.

52
00:05:33,367 --> 00:05:35,300
What'll it be?

53
00:05:35,369 --> 00:05:38,303
Oh, I don't know.
I'm a mess.

54
00:05:38,372 --> 00:05:40,805
What did you
have in mind?

55
00:05:46,013 --> 00:05:49,314
Whiskey.
What a surprise.

56
00:05:54,821 --> 00:05:57,289
This here's
the Ferguson place.

57
00:06:01,128 --> 00:06:04,162
Let me help you
down here, ma'am.

58
00:06:04,231 --> 00:06:06,264
Watch your step.

59
00:06:08,568 --> 00:06:12,304
Aah!

60
00:06:13,640 --> 00:06:15,573
Son of a bitch!

61
00:06:15,642 --> 00:06:17,909
Arggh!

62
00:06:17,978 --> 00:06:20,011
Are you sure about this?

63
00:06:20,080 --> 00:06:22,013
Quite sure.

64
00:06:22,082 --> 00:06:25,516
Well... good-bye.

65
00:06:25,585 --> 00:06:28,253
And good luck.

66
00:06:30,657 --> 00:06:32,623
Good-bye.

67
00:06:32,692 --> 00:06:34,759
Hyah!

68
00:06:49,443 --> 00:06:53,311
- Aaah!
- Ohh!

69
00:07:00,387 --> 00:07:02,753
- Ooh!
- Two!

70
00:07:02,822 --> 00:07:05,590
- Whoo!
- Excuse me!

71
00:07:07,094 --> 00:07:11,229
Excuse me.
Hello.
Ooh.

72
00:07:11,298 --> 00:07:13,465
- Hello.
- Huh?

73
00:07:13,533 --> 00:07:16,634
Oooh!

74
00:07:16,703 --> 00:07:18,636
Hello.

75
00:07:18,705 --> 00:07:22,673
My name
is Lindsey thurlow.

76
00:07:22,742 --> 00:07:24,842
Huh?

77
00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:27,979
The mail-order bride.
Huh huh.

78
00:07:28,048 --> 00:07:30,748
Which one of you
is the groom?

79
00:07:33,220 --> 00:07:35,487
None of US could afford
a bride on his own,

80
00:07:35,555 --> 00:07:38,656
so we all just sort of...
Pitched in.

81
00:07:38,725 --> 00:07:41,726
This is completely
unacceptable.

82
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:45,030
My contract was signed
by a, uh...

83
00:07:45,098 --> 00:07:47,198
Mr. Clayton Ferguson.

84
00:07:47,267 --> 00:07:50,402
He's in the barn.

85
00:07:51,804 --> 00:07:56,074
Thank god.
Ohh! Thank god!

86
00:07:56,143 --> 00:07:59,010
Millie, come back,
darlin'!

87
00:07:59,079 --> 00:08:01,746
I was only jokin'!

88
00:08:03,250 --> 00:08:05,783
Women!

89
00:08:07,554 --> 00:08:09,654
They're always
arguing.

90
00:08:11,658 --> 00:08:13,824
Huh huh huh...

91
00:08:13,893 --> 00:08:15,893
Right.

92
00:08:17,097 --> 00:08:19,997
What'll it be--
whiskey.

93
00:08:28,408 --> 00:08:30,341
Hey, Ferguson.
Is it raining?

94
00:08:30,410 --> 00:08:34,312
I thought
we was in drought.

95
00:08:34,381 --> 00:08:38,550
Oh.

96
00:08:38,618 --> 00:08:40,918
Oh, god.

97
00:08:44,023 --> 00:08:46,857
You got a problem,
there, mister?

98
00:08:46,926 --> 00:08:49,494
Uh, yeah.
These are my cows.

99
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:55,066
You see?
They say "Phil's cow,"

100
00:08:55,135 --> 00:08:58,103
and, uh, hey, I'm Phil.

101
00:08:58,171 --> 00:09:01,606
They were stolen from me
about two nights ago.

102
00:09:01,674 --> 00:09:04,842
Ahh!
You must be mistaken.

103
00:09:04,911 --> 00:09:10,848
I bought these cows
last year in...
Dodge.

104
00:09:11,918 --> 00:09:14,085
Of course, you got
a problem with that,

105
00:09:14,154 --> 00:09:16,087
we can settle it
right here.

106
00:09:16,156 --> 00:09:20,592
That's life, huh?
I don't much like
being called a...

107
00:09:20,660 --> 00:09:24,195
Cattle rustler.
I don't blame you.

108
00:09:25,965 --> 00:09:30,401
Take 10 paces.
Say, I'd love to,
but I can't,

109
00:09:30,470 --> 00:09:33,404
because you know what?
I'm antihandgun.

110
00:09:33,473 --> 00:09:36,574
So, uh...
Let's see.

111
00:09:38,345 --> 00:09:41,513
What do you say
we flip for them?

112
00:09:41,581 --> 00:09:45,283
I said take 10 paces,
turn, and start shootin'.

113
00:09:47,187 --> 00:09:49,120
Those are cows!

114
00:09:49,189 --> 00:09:52,323
What am I, crazy?
What have I been thinkin'?

115
00:09:52,392 --> 00:09:54,392
I'm a sheep rancher!

116
00:09:54,461 --> 00:09:56,661
Ha ha ha!

117
00:09:56,729 --> 00:09:58,663
Start walkin'!

118
00:10:00,467 --> 00:10:02,683
1... 2...

119
00:10:02,752 --> 00:10:06,304
3... 4...

120
00:10:06,373 --> 00:10:08,373
What comes after 4?

121
00:10:10,043 --> 00:10:11,976
4 1/2.

122
00:10:12,045 --> 00:10:15,112
4 1/2... 5...

123
00:10:17,317 --> 00:10:19,250
8, 9--

124
00:10:22,823 --> 00:10:25,423
where the hell
did he go?

125
00:10:27,227 --> 00:10:32,664
I can't face
another wounded teller
with a workman's comp claim!

126
00:10:32,733 --> 00:10:35,667
He took the book
to the outhouse...

127
00:10:35,736 --> 00:10:38,169
And used it
as toilet paper!

128
00:10:38,238 --> 00:10:40,772
No more ious,
no more rocks!

129
00:10:40,841 --> 00:10:43,241
What were
we thinking?

130
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:45,943
Why did we come out here?

131
00:10:46,012 --> 00:10:49,681
Why don't we go back?
What?
What?

132
00:10:49,750 --> 00:10:53,551
Yeah, back east.
Back home.
Back. Come on.

133
00:10:53,620 --> 00:10:56,254
- You're talkin' crazy.
- Am I?

134
00:10:56,322 --> 00:10:59,090
We can't go east.
Why not?

135
00:10:59,158 --> 00:11:02,226
Because.
because it's
against the code.

136
00:11:02,295 --> 00:11:05,730
Exactly.
It's against the code.
What code?

137
00:11:05,799 --> 00:11:09,233
You know what code.
The code of the west.

138
00:11:09,302 --> 00:11:11,770
Oh, the code of the west.

139
00:11:11,838 --> 00:11:14,105
The same code
that says, uh...

140
00:11:14,173 --> 00:11:16,207
"The only good Indian
is a dead Indian."

141
00:11:16,276 --> 00:11:18,576
And "die with your boots on."

142
00:11:18,645 --> 00:11:22,881
Wait. I got another one--
"if someone steals
your horse, you hang 'em."

143
00:11:22,949 --> 00:11:24,949
That's some code.

144
00:11:25,018 --> 00:11:27,051
Quite a code.
Let's stay.

145
00:11:27,120 --> 00:11:29,053
Admittedly not
an enlightened ideology.

146
00:11:29,122 --> 00:11:32,056
But leaving would be
like giving up.

147
00:11:32,125 --> 00:11:34,926
That's exactly what
it would be, Ben.

148
00:11:34,994 --> 00:11:36,994
So let's just give up.

149
00:11:37,063 --> 00:11:39,931
Let's get a wagon master
and go home.

150
00:11:39,999 --> 00:11:42,834
Let's go east.
What do you say?

151
00:11:42,903 --> 00:11:45,970
I say you're gutless,
yellow-bellied,
eastern sissies!

152
00:11:46,039 --> 00:11:49,441
All you done
since you got here
is whine and complain!

153
00:11:49,509 --> 00:11:53,478
Go back and leave the west
to the real men!

154
00:11:53,547 --> 00:11:57,482
I could have the books
on the wagon really quickly,

155
00:11:57,551 --> 00:12:00,852
and the cappuccino machine
travels like a dream.

156
00:12:00,921 --> 00:12:04,088
Henrietta misses
her family back east.

157
00:12:04,157 --> 00:12:07,725
I could take care
of my girls,
settle my ious--

158
00:12:07,794 --> 00:12:10,227
wait!

159
00:12:10,296 --> 00:12:12,296
We need a sign.

160
00:12:12,365 --> 00:12:14,899
Sign?
From the lord.

161
00:12:14,968 --> 00:12:17,469
Actually, a sign
would be terrific.

162
00:12:17,537 --> 00:12:19,504
Oh! Oh, that's right.

163
00:12:27,481 --> 00:12:30,982
Hey, Zeke, come on.
Really, there's your sign.

164
00:12:31,050 --> 00:12:34,486
When was the last time
it rained here, huh?

165
00:12:34,554 --> 00:12:37,689
That's not a sign.
It's just rain.

166
00:12:48,201 --> 00:12:51,102
Zeke,
that is a major sign.

167
00:12:51,170 --> 00:12:53,471
It's just the wind, Phil.

168
00:12:53,540 --> 00:12:55,507
Tough room, Phil.

169
00:13:06,486 --> 00:13:09,086
Ooh!

170
00:13:09,155 --> 00:13:11,890
Oh, dear.

171
00:13:11,958 --> 00:13:15,793
- That...
- That's a sign.

172
00:13:17,564 --> 00:13:19,864
What?

173
00:13:22,669 --> 00:13:25,803
- Ohh!
- Who's he?

174
00:13:25,872 --> 00:13:30,241
Who in the--
stranger?
Smells like whiskey.

175
00:13:30,309 --> 00:13:33,511
Well, he's certainly come
to the right place.

176
00:13:33,580 --> 00:13:35,513
I don't recognize him.

177
00:13:35,582 --> 00:13:38,516
Easy, slick!
You ain't a customer yet!

178
00:13:38,585 --> 00:13:42,319
Hands off!
"James h. Harlow."

179
00:13:44,024 --> 00:13:45,957
"Wagon master."

180
00:13:57,103 --> 00:13:59,203
Sure you're not hungry?

181
00:14:01,107 --> 00:14:04,042
I don't eat meat...
When I'm drinkin'.

182
00:14:04,110 --> 00:14:06,044
Ha ha ha!

183
00:14:06,112 --> 00:14:09,047
Look, I know he looks
a little unsteady,

184
00:14:09,115 --> 00:14:12,784
but there's
something about him--
something in his eyes.

185
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:16,287
Those are blood vessels.
The man's a drunk.

186
00:14:16,355 --> 00:14:19,791
It could be pinkeye.
There's a lot going around.

187
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:24,295
Listen, could you go
through that route again
for US, huh?

188
00:14:24,363 --> 00:14:26,297
Follow me.

189
00:14:32,639 --> 00:14:35,073
Gentlemen...

190
00:14:35,141 --> 00:14:38,175
This is the southwest
territories.

191
00:14:38,244 --> 00:14:40,411
We're going to start here.

192
00:14:40,480 --> 00:14:42,513
Here's chimney rock.

193
00:14:43,817 --> 00:14:45,817
Over here's
devil's gate.

194
00:14:47,053 --> 00:14:49,921
No, no, no.
This is--

195
00:14:49,990 --> 00:14:52,991
aah! Aah!

196
00:14:53,059 --> 00:14:55,994
Platte river.
Now I know
where I am.

197
00:14:56,062 --> 00:14:58,830
Can't you just
use a map?

198
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:01,298
I don't use maps,
Earl.

199
00:15:01,367 --> 00:15:03,367
Ben!

200
00:15:05,238 --> 00:15:08,706
Ben.
Got it all up here...

201
00:15:08,775 --> 00:15:12,010
Where it counts!
Mmm.

202
00:15:12,078 --> 00:15:15,747
That's what
I'm afraid of.
Can we go, Phil?

203
00:15:15,815 --> 00:15:18,750
Hold on. Let me
get this straight.

204
00:15:18,818 --> 00:15:21,252
This Dutch oven's
our first campsite.

205
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:24,255
Right. Right next to
the Pawnee nation.

206
00:15:24,323 --> 00:15:28,993
No, that can't be
the Pawnee nation.
They're not that unified.

207
00:15:29,062 --> 00:15:32,496
Pawnee'd be more like
this here muffin tin.

208
00:15:32,565 --> 00:15:34,498
We cannot
entrust the lives...

209
00:15:34,567 --> 00:15:37,501
Of our families
and friends to this...

210
00:15:37,570 --> 00:15:39,537
Drunken lunatic!

211
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:42,040
With all due respect.

212
00:15:42,108 --> 00:15:45,910
Respect... taken.

213
00:15:48,614 --> 00:15:50,614
Oh, mister...

214
00:15:52,118 --> 00:15:55,553
I don't blame you
for doubtin' my abilities.

215
00:15:55,621 --> 00:15:58,056
You'd be a fool
not to.

216
00:15:58,124 --> 00:16:01,059
Been a drunk for
the last 20 years.

217
00:16:03,129 --> 00:16:05,830
But I know this land!

218
00:16:05,899 --> 00:16:08,700
I just need a chance.

219
00:16:08,768 --> 00:16:10,702
It ain't about
the money,

220
00:16:10,770 --> 00:16:12,704
I'll leave that
to you.

221
00:16:12,772 --> 00:16:14,706
But you folks...

222
00:16:14,774 --> 00:16:16,908
You need
a wagon master,

223
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:18,976
and, well...

224
00:16:28,654 --> 00:16:31,089
I'd like it
to be me.

225
00:16:31,157 --> 00:16:35,459
- Well, I guess you're
our man, Harlow.
- What?

226
00:16:35,528 --> 00:16:38,196
Thank you, Jerry.

227
00:16:38,264 --> 00:16:40,965
Well, actually, it's...
It's, uh, Phil.

228
00:16:41,034 --> 00:16:43,334
You won't be sorry.

229
00:16:49,175 --> 00:16:51,175
Oh, my!

230
00:16:52,545 --> 00:16:54,612
Ladies.

231
00:17:03,056 --> 00:17:05,723
We leave at dawn.

232
00:17:09,829 --> 00:17:11,929
Noonish.

233
00:17:19,105 --> 00:17:21,505
Hey, there--
there he is!

234
00:17:23,843 --> 00:17:28,212
- Hey, that looks like
a wagon master to me.
- Whoa!

235
00:17:35,989 --> 00:17:39,791
- People ready, Mr. Taylor?
- Yes, sir!

236
00:17:39,859 --> 00:17:42,226
All right.
Mount your wagons!

237
00:17:42,295 --> 00:17:45,897
Wagons, ho!

238
00:17:45,965 --> 00:17:47,999
Go on! Go on!

239
00:17:57,543 --> 00:18:00,211
Wagon master.
Yoo-hoo!

240
00:18:02,381 --> 00:18:04,315
Yoo-hoo!

241
00:18:19,532 --> 00:18:21,465
When I say "wagons, ho,"

242
00:18:21,534 --> 00:18:25,903
that's the signal
that y'all pull out
and follow me.

243
00:18:25,972 --> 00:18:27,905
You're going
the wrong way.

244
00:18:27,974 --> 00:18:31,709
Ben, we never told him
where we were going.

245
00:18:31,777 --> 00:18:33,911
Is this some
guessing game?

246
00:18:33,980 --> 00:18:38,482
No, no, no, no.
We're, uh...
Going, uh, east.

247
00:18:40,019 --> 00:18:44,322
- East?
- Do you have a problem
with that?

248
00:18:44,390 --> 00:18:48,559
I don't know.
Don't seem right.
I've always gone west.

249
00:18:48,627 --> 00:18:52,864
Well, we're going east.
Do you want the job
or not?

250
00:18:53,900 --> 00:18:57,534
Wagons...

251
00:18:57,603 --> 00:18:59,770
East!

252
00:19:04,577 --> 00:19:06,577
Come on!

253
00:19:27,066 --> 00:19:29,901
Bye, Julian!

254
00:19:47,353 --> 00:19:52,523
Gentlemen, gentlemen.
If I could have your attention
for a moment, please.

255
00:19:52,591 --> 00:19:55,293
Thank you.
Thank you so much.
Now, as you know,

256
00:19:55,361 --> 00:19:57,795
the success of our
transcontinental railroad...

257
00:19:57,863 --> 00:20:00,731
Depends upon the success
of the land rush...

258
00:20:00,800 --> 00:20:03,200
Scheduled
for the 4th of July.

259
00:20:03,269 --> 00:20:05,669
President Grant
has made it clear,

260
00:20:05,738 --> 00:20:09,140
if the population isn't
built up in the west,

261
00:20:09,208 --> 00:20:13,110
we don't get any more money
to subsidize our railroad.

262
00:20:13,179 --> 00:20:15,546
Tom, let's hear your report.

263
00:20:15,614 --> 00:20:18,182
People are camped
on top of each other.

264
00:20:18,251 --> 00:20:20,284
To use their terms,

265
00:20:20,353 --> 00:20:23,454
"they're chompin' at the bit
and rarin' to git..."

266
00:20:23,522 --> 00:20:25,556
Ha ha!

267
00:20:25,624 --> 00:20:29,560
As soon as they receive
the go-ahead July 4th.

268
00:20:29,628 --> 00:20:32,063
Wait, wait, wait,
wait, wait. Mmm!

269
00:20:32,131 --> 00:20:34,065
Before we count
our chickens,

270
00:20:34,133 --> 00:20:38,336
listen to this telegram
from a couple agents
out west.

271
00:20:38,404 --> 00:20:42,340
"Have learned
of a wagon train
planning to head east.

272
00:20:42,408 --> 00:20:44,342
"Repeat-- east.

273
00:20:44,410 --> 00:20:47,378
"Five wagons in all.
Possible trend?

274
00:20:47,447 --> 00:20:49,380
Stop--
please advise."

275
00:20:49,449 --> 00:20:53,184
Now, gentlemen,
I submit to you,
there goes the west.

276
00:20:53,252 --> 00:20:55,186
Ha ha ha!

277
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:58,189
I just hope
it's not too late...

278
00:20:58,257 --> 00:21:01,292
To give
Washington back
the $100 million.

279
00:21:04,063 --> 00:21:06,730
Quiet!

280
00:21:06,799 --> 00:21:09,833
Let me see that.

281
00:21:13,339 --> 00:21:15,739
Will you take
that off, already?

282
00:21:15,808 --> 00:21:18,709
I can't believe
my own father's a quitter.

283
00:21:18,777 --> 00:21:22,980
Stop saying that.
Just because a man
decides to quit...

284
00:21:23,049 --> 00:21:25,015
Doesn't make him a--
you know.

285
00:21:25,084 --> 00:21:28,018
Well, I guess
it does, doesn't it?

286
00:21:28,087 --> 00:21:30,520
All right, then,
I'm a quitter.

287
00:21:30,589 --> 00:21:33,023
But there's no
shame in quitting.

288
00:21:33,092 --> 00:21:35,525
This country was
founded by quitters--

289
00:21:35,594 --> 00:21:38,528
English quitters,
French quitters,
German quitters.

290
00:21:38,597 --> 00:21:41,531
For your information,
if not for quitters,

291
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:43,868
no one would
start anything.

292
00:21:45,938 --> 00:21:48,038
And buckle up.

293
00:21:48,107 --> 00:21:51,242
Howdy, Phil.
How you doin', Zeke?

294
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:56,046
- What's that wagon master
fella's name again?
- You mean Harlow.

295
00:21:56,115 --> 00:22:00,417
Yep. Been gnawin' at me
since I set eyes on him.

296
00:22:00,486 --> 00:22:02,753
You don't forget
somebody like that.

297
00:22:02,821 --> 00:22:05,356
Why?
What did he do?

298
00:22:05,424 --> 00:22:08,192
That's the only part
I can't remember.

299
00:22:08,261 --> 00:22:11,262
- Something really good...
- Yeah?

300
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:13,697
- Or really bad.
- Oh.

301
00:22:13,766 --> 00:22:15,699
You must remember
something.

302
00:22:15,768 --> 00:22:19,736
It'll come to me.
You can be sure of it.

303
00:22:21,807 --> 00:22:23,807
Maybe not.

304
00:22:28,514 --> 00:22:32,549
Howdy, ma'am.
I didn't properly
introduce myself.

305
00:22:32,618 --> 00:22:34,551
The name's Harlow.

306
00:22:34,620 --> 00:22:36,987
I'll be
your wagon master.

307
00:22:37,056 --> 00:22:39,689
I'd say
the jury's still out.

308
00:22:39,758 --> 00:22:42,359
Pretty quick
to judge a man, aren't you?

309
00:22:42,428 --> 00:22:47,497
In my line of work,
it takes no time at all.

310
00:22:47,566 --> 00:22:51,268
I'd like to prove you
wrong one day, ma'am.

311
00:22:51,337 --> 00:22:54,204
Oh!
my doll!

312
00:22:54,273 --> 00:22:57,141
Excuse me, ma'am. Ho!

313
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:10,321
Yes!

314
00:23:14,327 --> 00:23:16,893
Ohh!

315
00:23:16,963 --> 00:23:20,097
- Ohh!
- Oh...

316
00:23:20,166 --> 00:23:22,166
Ma'am.

317
00:23:25,104 --> 00:23:28,038
Come on!
Yah!

318
00:23:39,018 --> 00:23:42,052
Move it out!
Come on!

319
00:23:44,123 --> 00:23:47,557
How many wagons
did we start with, Phil?

320
00:23:47,626 --> 00:23:50,560
Five. Why?
Did we lose one?

321
00:23:50,629 --> 00:23:52,562
Nope.
Gained a couple.

322
00:23:52,631 --> 00:23:54,898
Shoot, we're turning
into a movement.

323
00:23:54,967 --> 00:23:57,034
How do you like that?

324
00:23:57,103 --> 00:23:59,536
I don't like
it one bit.

325
00:23:59,605 --> 00:24:01,538
Fix this.

326
00:24:01,607 --> 00:24:03,540
Not now,
you nincompoop.

327
00:24:03,609 --> 00:24:05,542
Uh, j.P...

328
00:24:05,611 --> 00:24:08,545
You know, they have
just picked up...

329
00:24:08,614 --> 00:24:11,548
A few stragglers--
one or two wagons.

330
00:24:11,617 --> 00:24:13,717
They're clearing out
the deadwood for US.

331
00:24:13,785 --> 00:24:15,719
Deadwood. Yes.

332
00:24:15,787 --> 00:24:20,157
I'd like to clear out
some deadwood from
around here.

333
00:24:20,226 --> 00:24:24,895
You're dismissed, smedly.
Dismissed--
dismissed, sir?

334
00:24:24,963 --> 00:24:29,333
Wait, sir.
I-I've been with
the company 20 years.

335
00:24:29,402 --> 00:24:32,269
Not fired,
you sniveling idiot.

336
00:24:32,338 --> 00:24:35,339
Dismissed!
Now, get out!
Oh, yes, of course.

337
00:24:35,408 --> 00:24:38,308
- Wait a minute.
- Yes, sir.

338
00:24:38,377 --> 00:24:42,812
Take a letter.
I'm just going to
use your pen.

339
00:24:42,881 --> 00:24:45,416
No, you're not.
No, I'm not.

340
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:47,684
Go ahead.
I'll remember.

341
00:24:47,753 --> 00:24:51,688
Address it to
Mr. John Slade...
Mr. John Slade...

342
00:24:51,757 --> 00:24:55,192
Somewhere on
the high plains.
John Slade... the high plains.

343
00:24:55,261 --> 00:24:57,494
Dear Mr. Slade...
John Slade, high plains,
Mr. Slade.

344
00:24:57,563 --> 00:25:02,566
Something of great
importance requires your
immediate attention.

345
00:25:02,634 --> 00:25:04,768
...immediate attention.
Dear Mr. John...

346
00:25:25,424 --> 00:25:29,359
Whoa, whoa!
Easy, Mr. Slade, easy.
Pony express.

347
00:25:29,428 --> 00:25:32,296
I got a telegraph
for you.

348
00:25:44,577 --> 00:25:48,078
If I could get you
to sign right here.

349
00:25:58,124 --> 00:26:01,291
Unusual signature
you have there.

350
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:04,628
Two more stops,
and I'm done for the day.

351
00:26:04,696 --> 00:26:06,663
Which way is abilene?

352
00:26:06,732 --> 00:26:08,698
That way.

353
00:26:08,767 --> 00:26:12,402
Okay. And, uh,
what about Denver?

354
00:26:12,471 --> 00:26:14,904
Ooh!

355
00:26:14,973 --> 00:26:17,907
Dead ahead.

356
00:26:21,680 --> 00:26:24,615
It's been two hours,
for god's sake.

357
00:26:24,683 --> 00:26:27,618
Ben, there's a fork
in the road.

358
00:26:27,686 --> 00:26:30,120
This is a very
important decision.

359
00:26:30,189 --> 00:26:33,123
The man's got to use
all his instincts,

360
00:26:33,192 --> 00:26:35,626
get the lay
of the land,

361
00:26:35,694 --> 00:26:37,628
the angle
of the sun,

362
00:26:37,696 --> 00:26:39,663
the position
of the moon.

363
00:26:39,731 --> 00:26:43,300
Which way are we--

364
00:26:51,443 --> 00:26:53,877
Uhh!

365
00:26:53,945 --> 00:26:56,880
Yeah! Yeah. Yeah.

366
00:26:56,948 --> 00:27:00,384
So which way
do we go, huh?

367
00:27:00,452 --> 00:27:03,387
That way.
You sure?

368
00:27:03,455 --> 00:27:06,657
I know which way
we're going.

369
00:27:06,725 --> 00:27:10,760
Wagons...

370
00:27:10,829 --> 00:27:14,531
Ho!
Hyah!

371
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:17,901
Hyah!

372
00:27:21,140 --> 00:27:24,041
Hyah!
Hyah!

373
00:27:31,016 --> 00:27:33,450
That's enough,
already.

374
00:27:33,519 --> 00:27:36,953
"I know which way
we're going."

375
00:27:37,022 --> 00:27:40,757
It was his first mistake.
It was his first
decision.

376
00:27:40,825 --> 00:27:44,528
Hope there aren't
any more forks
in the road.

377
00:27:44,596 --> 00:27:48,031
Hope there ain't
no more forks
in the road.

378
00:27:48,100 --> 00:27:51,201
That's the last time
I listen to you.

379
00:27:51,270 --> 00:27:54,271
Told you
to wake me up.

380
00:28:10,655 --> 00:28:12,589
Are you all right,
miss?

381
00:28:12,657 --> 00:28:14,591
Oh. Yes, I'm fine.

382
00:28:16,161 --> 00:28:18,928
No, you're not.
You're crying.

383
00:28:21,567 --> 00:28:23,733
It's the fergusons.

384
00:28:23,802 --> 00:28:26,002
They're driving me mad.

385
00:28:26,071 --> 00:28:30,574
I've been
staving off their advances
since we left prosperity.

386
00:28:30,642 --> 00:28:33,810
Well, you don't
have to stay with them.

387
00:28:33,878 --> 00:28:36,012
You could ride with me.

388
00:28:36,081 --> 00:28:38,315
Thank you.

389
00:28:38,383 --> 00:28:40,317
I couldn't, though!

390
00:28:40,385 --> 00:28:43,853
You don't
owe them anything.
Yes, I do.

391
00:28:43,922 --> 00:28:46,356
My family accepted
money from them...

392
00:28:46,425 --> 00:28:48,858
In exchange
for my hand.

393
00:28:48,927 --> 00:28:51,661
Ha ha ha!

394
00:28:51,730 --> 00:28:54,063
We've got a contract.

395
00:28:54,133 --> 00:28:56,065
Well, that's
just not fair.

396
00:28:56,135 --> 00:28:58,635
Oh, boy!
oh, my gosh!

397
00:28:58,703 --> 00:29:01,471
Whoa!
Whoo whoo whoo!

398
00:29:01,540 --> 00:29:05,708
What in the hell
are they doing
over there, anyway?

399
00:29:05,777 --> 00:29:09,613
Oh! Well, they're
lighting their farts afire.

400
00:29:09,681 --> 00:29:11,615
What else?

401
00:29:11,683 --> 00:29:13,950
You got one, Harry?

402
00:29:14,019 --> 00:29:16,853
Whooo!
ehh!

403
00:29:36,241 --> 00:29:38,241
Ha ha!

404
00:29:49,954 --> 00:29:51,988
Halt! Who goes there?

405
00:29:53,392 --> 00:29:55,825
Just wanted
a cup of coffee.

406
00:29:55,894 --> 00:29:58,861
I ain't never seen
you before.

407
00:30:01,032 --> 00:30:03,667
I'm the new guy.

408
00:30:05,737 --> 00:30:10,507
Oh. Sure!
The new guy!
Ha ha ha!

409
00:30:51,583 --> 00:30:53,583
Ahh.

410
00:31:08,367 --> 00:31:10,299
Vultures!

411
00:31:10,368 --> 00:31:13,770
Someone's gonna die!

412
00:31:13,838 --> 00:31:16,339
Honey!

413
00:31:21,112 --> 00:31:23,546
Where the hell's
the river, Harlow?

414
00:31:23,615 --> 00:31:26,949
- We're almost there.
- You've said that
two days ago.

415
00:31:27,018 --> 00:31:29,085
It was
a day and a half.

416
00:31:29,154 --> 00:31:32,389
My wife's
dying of thirst.
Oh, no. I'm fine.

417
00:31:32,457 --> 00:31:34,291
Look there.

418
00:31:34,359 --> 00:31:37,226
Two sisters.
What?

419
00:31:37,296 --> 00:31:41,398
Two sisters.
Sweetwater's on the other side.

420
00:31:41,466 --> 00:31:45,535
- Water!
- Yes!

421
00:31:45,604 --> 00:31:48,104
Oh!

422
00:31:57,248 --> 00:31:58,682
Yeeha!

423
00:32:00,852 --> 00:32:02,151
Hyah!

424
00:32:08,092 --> 00:32:10,960
Come on, everybody!
Come on!

425
00:32:15,300 --> 00:32:17,467
Oh, no.
Sweetwater, huh?

426
00:32:17,536 --> 00:32:21,471
What the heck
is this?

427
00:32:29,047 --> 00:32:32,482
This ought to be good.
Yeah.

428
00:32:36,054 --> 00:32:39,422
River must have
changed course.

429
00:32:39,491 --> 00:32:42,325
I guess a lot of things
change in 20 years.

430
00:32:42,394 --> 00:32:45,462
- We trusted you.
- I never trusted him.

431
00:32:45,530 --> 00:32:49,833
- We should string him up.
- I get his boots!

432
00:32:49,901 --> 00:32:51,835
Go find a tree,
junior.

433
00:32:51,903 --> 00:32:54,170
I found the tree
last time.

434
00:32:54,239 --> 00:32:58,441
- There ain't trees here.
- I say we Bury him alive.

435
00:32:58,510 --> 00:33:02,879
Go find a shovel.
Give me that.

436
00:33:02,947 --> 00:33:07,049
Do something.
Run, Harlow!

437
00:33:07,118 --> 00:33:10,019
Come back here, now.

438
00:33:10,088 --> 00:33:13,356
- Whoa!
- No!

439
00:33:13,425 --> 00:33:17,360
Oh!

440
00:33:17,429 --> 00:33:20,397
Water!
Look at that!

441
00:33:20,465 --> 00:33:23,366
- Water!
- How deep is it?

442
00:33:23,435 --> 00:33:26,903
Deep!
There's a sand bar
over here.

443
00:33:26,971 --> 00:33:28,805
Yeeow!

444
00:33:30,742 --> 00:33:32,975
Oh, dear.

445
00:33:39,618 --> 00:33:41,951
Let's go!
Keep it moving!

446
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:43,620
Come on, now!

447
00:33:43,688 --> 00:33:47,757
Wagons, ho!

448
00:33:47,826 --> 00:33:50,760
Honey, please keep
two hands on the reins.

449
00:33:50,829 --> 00:33:52,796
Stop telling me
how to drive!

450
00:33:58,937 --> 00:34:02,038
- Move!
- Yeeah!

451
00:34:02,106 --> 00:34:04,106
That's it, belle!

452
00:34:10,449 --> 00:34:13,716
- Aah!
- Ha ha ha!

453
00:34:19,524 --> 00:34:21,724
Come on! Come on!

454
00:34:21,793 --> 00:34:26,563
Now, you shut up!
I ain't asked you
no questions.

455
00:34:26,631 --> 00:34:28,030
Ow!

456
00:34:32,571 --> 00:34:36,238
You stop!
Wait for me!

457
00:34:39,310 --> 00:34:41,511
I'm gonna get you!

458
00:34:41,580 --> 00:34:44,180
We're almost there.

459
00:34:46,985 --> 00:34:49,051
I don't believe this!

460
00:34:57,395 --> 00:35:00,062
What are you
looking at?

461
00:35:03,434 --> 00:35:05,635
Come on, now!

462
00:35:07,205 --> 00:35:09,806
You people are crazy.

463
00:35:09,875 --> 00:35:12,441
Whoa!

464
00:35:12,511 --> 00:35:17,146
Crazy? What do
you mean, crazy?

465
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:19,148
Because we risked our lives
crossing a river...

466
00:35:19,217 --> 00:35:21,150
Instead of staying
on the other side?

467
00:35:21,219 --> 00:35:24,654
Because we have faith
in ourselves?

468
00:35:24,723 --> 00:35:28,625
Because we believe in
a wagon master...

469
00:35:28,693 --> 00:35:32,896
Who gave US the confidence
to do things we never
thought we could?

470
00:35:32,964 --> 00:35:37,233
No. Because most people
use the bridge.

471
00:35:43,408 --> 00:35:46,709
"If river crossing
any indication,

472
00:35:46,778 --> 00:35:49,579
"see little reason
to worry. Stop.

473
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:52,949
"Party seems certain
to self-destruct. Stop.

474
00:35:53,018 --> 00:35:56,485
"Will proceed with plan,
however. Stop. Slade."

475
00:35:56,555 --> 00:35:59,155
Little reason
to worry. Ha!

476
00:35:59,223 --> 00:36:01,558
Ha!
It's not his money,
is it?

477
00:36:01,626 --> 00:36:04,226
No, sir.
I want those
defectors eliminated.

478
00:36:04,295 --> 00:36:07,229
If Mr. Bad-man Slade
can't do it,

479
00:36:07,298 --> 00:36:10,833
- I'll find
someone who can!
- Yes, sir.

480
00:36:10,902 --> 00:36:14,871
I'm going
down to Washington
to do some lobbying.

481
00:36:14,940 --> 00:36:16,739
I want that
wagons east movement...

482
00:36:16,808 --> 00:36:20,509
Monitored very closely
in my absence.
Yes, sir!

483
00:36:20,579 --> 00:36:23,880
Well, how do I look?
Fat, sir.

484
00:36:23,949 --> 00:36:28,184
Rich! Rich, sir!
Fat-- fat with money.

485
00:36:28,252 --> 00:36:32,321
Jeremiah's on my side!
You kids
cut it out now!

486
00:36:32,390 --> 00:36:35,324
Jeremiah started it.
"Jeremiah started it"!

487
00:36:35,393 --> 00:36:38,061
Stop it!
Hey! Come on!

488
00:36:38,129 --> 00:36:41,064
Why'd he have to
come along anyway?

489
00:36:41,132 --> 00:36:44,467
- Because he's your brother.
- Are you sure?

490
00:36:44,535 --> 00:36:48,337
I'll have your mother
turn this wagon around
right now!

491
00:36:48,406 --> 00:36:51,474
Are we there yet?
Are we there yet?

492
00:36:51,542 --> 00:36:54,978
I am warning you two.

493
00:36:55,046 --> 00:36:58,380
Dad...
What is it, prudence?

494
00:36:58,449 --> 00:37:02,051
I have to go
to the bathroom.

495
00:37:03,554 --> 00:37:06,623
Why didn't you go
at dead horse bend?

496
00:37:06,691 --> 00:37:09,358
I didn't
have to go then.

497
00:37:09,427 --> 00:37:12,762
Can you hold it till
the devil's skillet?
No!

498
00:37:12,831 --> 00:37:15,665
Whoa!

499
00:37:25,043 --> 00:37:27,477
Turn around!

500
00:37:42,560 --> 00:37:46,062
Wagons, ho!

501
00:37:46,131 --> 00:37:48,465
Buckle up.

502
00:37:49,534 --> 00:37:52,135
Hyah!

503
00:37:55,107 --> 00:37:57,040
Pa?

504
00:37:57,109 --> 00:37:59,476
I think
I should have...

505
00:37:59,544 --> 00:38:02,412
Gotten off
back there, too.

506
00:38:04,549 --> 00:38:06,483
Mm-hmm.

507
00:38:10,688 --> 00:38:12,688
Ha ha ha!

508
00:38:31,076 --> 00:38:33,009
Hey, thanks.

509
00:38:34,579 --> 00:38:36,513
You got a problem, kid?

510
00:38:36,581 --> 00:38:39,015
No! No problem
at all.

511
00:38:51,096 --> 00:38:53,530
Thanks.

512
00:38:59,604 --> 00:39:01,538
The map can't be wrong.

513
00:39:01,606 --> 00:39:04,541
This ain't the way
to St. Louis.

514
00:39:04,609 --> 00:39:06,543
He knows the way, Ben.

515
00:39:06,611 --> 00:39:11,514
The river wasn't where
you thought it would be.
Phil.

516
00:39:11,583 --> 00:39:15,017
Well, Harlow, you don't
put much stock in maps,

517
00:39:15,087 --> 00:39:19,021
but I think we should trust
the United States army.

518
00:39:19,091 --> 00:39:22,024
Why?
maybe it's considered
more reliable...

519
00:39:22,094 --> 00:39:25,161
Than a stack of skillets
and muffin pans.

520
00:39:25,230 --> 00:39:28,965
He got US across
the river, didn't he?

521
00:39:29,033 --> 00:39:30,800
That's right.

522
00:39:30,868 --> 00:39:33,803
The river-- let's talk
about that decision.

523
00:39:33,871 --> 00:39:38,508
We should
have strung you up
back at the river.

524
00:39:38,577 --> 00:39:41,511
Fine!
You people don't listen
to nothing anyway!

525
00:39:41,580 --> 00:39:45,047
- You're just like the--
- who?

526
00:39:45,117 --> 00:39:47,950
Who, James?
never mind.

527
00:39:48,019 --> 00:39:50,420
Yeah! Never mind!

528
00:39:50,489 --> 00:39:54,157
Never mind yourself.
Never mind you.

529
00:39:54,226 --> 00:39:56,959
Never mind you!
no! Never mind you!

530
00:39:57,028 --> 00:39:58,995
I don't care!

531
00:39:59,063 --> 00:40:01,464
Wait! Wait!
what?

532
00:40:01,533 --> 00:40:04,467
Now I remember.
What?

533
00:40:04,536 --> 00:40:07,470
Harlow. James Harlow.
We know his name.

534
00:40:07,539 --> 00:40:09,972
He did something
really, really bad,

535
00:40:10,041 --> 00:40:12,975
like one of those horrible
acts against nature...

536
00:40:13,044 --> 00:40:15,478
That are just seared
into your brain.

537
00:40:15,547 --> 00:40:19,282
What was it?
I wish I could
remember!

538
00:40:19,351 --> 00:40:23,286
- Zeke!
- But I bet it's
eating away at him,

539
00:40:23,355 --> 00:40:25,355
sapping his confidence,

540
00:40:25,423 --> 00:40:27,990
clouding his judgment.

541
00:40:33,298 --> 00:40:36,232
I thought it might
be a good idea...

542
00:40:36,301 --> 00:40:40,736
If we took a break
from the pressures
of the trail,

543
00:40:40,805 --> 00:40:45,341
if we shared
our feelings as men
with other men...

544
00:40:45,410 --> 00:40:49,612
In the hopes that if
we got this old business
off our chests,

545
00:40:49,681 --> 00:40:52,715
it might make
our journey easier.

546
00:40:52,784 --> 00:40:56,052
Phil, what the hell
are you talking about?

547
00:40:56,120 --> 00:40:59,055
Just share something
personal with the group.

548
00:40:59,123 --> 00:41:01,791
You know,
some defining moment
from your past--

549
00:41:01,859 --> 00:41:03,893
a joyous memory,

550
00:41:03,961 --> 00:41:06,329
a broken dream.

551
00:41:06,398 --> 00:41:08,831
Who'd like to
go first? Harlow?

552
00:41:12,103 --> 00:41:15,638
Why don't you
start first, Phil?
This is your meeting.

553
00:41:15,707 --> 00:41:18,074
Yeah, it's
your meeting,
Phil.

554
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:21,077
I guess I could
start US off.

555
00:41:21,145 --> 00:41:26,583
I bet a lot of you guys
don't know that back
in St. Louis,

556
00:41:26,651 --> 00:41:30,353
I used to be a surgeon.

557
00:41:30,422 --> 00:41:34,424
I used to work
in a field hospital
during the war.

558
00:41:34,492 --> 00:41:40,396
It was a nightmare.
We'd work day and night.
We'd never sleep.

559
00:41:40,465 --> 00:41:43,099
We would eat
while we operated.

560
00:41:43,167 --> 00:41:47,337
Once, there was this young
soldier I was trying to save.

561
00:41:47,405 --> 00:41:49,405
He took a cannonball
to the stomach.

562
00:41:49,474 --> 00:41:52,575
Ha ha ha!

563
00:41:52,644 --> 00:41:55,878
It was a mess.
You can imagine.

564
00:41:55,947 --> 00:42:00,483
After 18 hours
of surgery, I did it.

565
00:42:00,552 --> 00:42:02,652
Of course you did!

566
00:42:02,721 --> 00:42:04,721
I never felt
better in my life,

567
00:42:04,789 --> 00:42:08,891
- until, just like that,
the patient dies.
- Oh, Phil.

568
00:42:08,960 --> 00:42:12,027
I left a Bologna sandwich
in his lung.

569
00:42:12,096 --> 00:42:14,230
Ha ha ha!

570
00:42:14,299 --> 00:42:16,633
That's enough!

571
00:42:16,701 --> 00:42:19,702
Well, put a shake
in my hand...

572
00:42:19,771 --> 00:42:23,072
And made it impossible
to use a scalpel.

573
00:42:23,141 --> 00:42:26,476
- I've got a better story.
- Go, Clayton!

574
00:42:26,544 --> 00:42:29,078
Well, go right ahead,
Clayton.

575
00:42:29,147 --> 00:42:32,081
I don't know
if any of you fellas...

576
00:42:32,150 --> 00:42:35,418
Remember what
it was like to be 13.

577
00:42:35,487 --> 00:42:39,188
You know-- the springtime
of your life...

578
00:42:39,257 --> 00:42:42,692
When the grass is greener,
the skies are bluer.

579
00:42:42,761 --> 00:42:45,895
You couldn't stop pulling
the wings off butterflies.

580
00:42:45,963 --> 00:42:50,500
Just about every time
you got within
100 feet of a female,

581
00:42:50,568 --> 00:42:54,737
put a little pup tent
in your britches.

582
00:42:54,806 --> 00:43:00,242
One day, I'm doing some
chores for old lady Connors.
That old hag.

583
00:43:00,312 --> 00:43:05,247
There she is,
napping on her bed
with her teeth in a glass...

584
00:43:05,317 --> 00:43:08,250
And her mouth
kind of slung open.

585
00:43:08,320 --> 00:43:11,754
I figure, what the heck.
It's a free country.

586
00:43:11,823 --> 00:43:16,526
- Clayton, you can finish
the story the next time.
- This is the best part.

587
00:43:16,594 --> 00:43:20,029
Mary's husband disappeared
for two hours last night.

588
00:43:20,097 --> 00:43:23,032
I saw her wagon rocking
the other night.

589
00:43:23,100 --> 00:43:26,969
Do you think
it was she
or the husband?

590
00:43:27,038 --> 00:43:30,306
Oh, please,
that woman--

591
00:43:42,053 --> 00:43:44,053
Ladies, listen...

592
00:43:44,121 --> 00:43:48,491
As long as we're all going
to be on this trip together,

593
00:43:48,560 --> 00:43:53,262
I think it's time we get
some things out in the open.

594
00:43:53,331 --> 00:43:58,234
Now, I've heard
the gossiping...

595
00:43:58,302 --> 00:44:00,236
And the whispering,

596
00:44:00,304 --> 00:44:04,206
and if there's something
you want to say,

597
00:44:04,275 --> 00:44:07,477
why don't you say it
to my face?

598
00:44:08,946 --> 00:44:10,913
What's it like?

599
00:44:10,982 --> 00:44:13,115
How much money
did you make?

600
00:44:13,184 --> 00:44:15,818
How do you
stay awake?

601
00:44:15,887 --> 00:44:19,989
- You don't actually
blow, do you?
- Blow what?

602
00:44:20,057 --> 00:44:22,759
Constance!

603
00:44:22,827 --> 00:44:28,464
Ladies! Ladies!
Oh, well, I'll tell you
anything you want.

604
00:44:28,533 --> 00:44:31,367
Uh, yeah.
You, henrietta.

605
00:44:31,436 --> 00:44:33,703
Uh... my husband told me...

606
00:44:33,772 --> 00:44:38,007
That the largest penis
ever recorded was 4 1/2 inches.

607
00:44:38,075 --> 00:44:40,142
Is that true?

608
00:44:45,617 --> 00:44:47,617
So, Harlow,

609
00:44:47,685 --> 00:44:50,620
you sure there's nothing
you'd like to share
with the group?

610
00:44:50,688 --> 00:44:53,989
About what?
Phil, I got one!

611
00:44:54,058 --> 00:44:56,492
About these dogs
that were stuck--

612
00:44:56,561 --> 00:44:58,861
Harry Bob,
terrific.

613
00:44:58,930 --> 00:45:00,963
Look here, Harry Bob.

614
00:45:01,032 --> 00:45:02,998
When I was 10 years old,

615
00:45:03,067 --> 00:45:06,469
I killed my best friend
Tommy hanley.

616
00:45:06,538 --> 00:45:09,639
The folks thought he died
falling out a tree.

617
00:45:09,707 --> 00:45:12,475
The fact of the matter is,

618
00:45:12,544 --> 00:45:17,647
I beat him with a club
then drug him in the woods
so's it'd look that way.

619
00:45:17,715 --> 00:45:19,649
Ha ha ha!

620
00:45:19,717 --> 00:45:22,718
I have no idea
why I done it.

621
00:45:24,489 --> 00:45:27,590
Ha ha ha!
Thank you, doctor.

622
00:45:27,659 --> 00:45:31,293
I feel better already.
We knowed it was you.

623
00:45:31,362 --> 00:45:34,163
No, you did not,
neither.
Yeah, we did.

624
00:45:34,231 --> 00:45:37,333
We knew.
No, you did not!

625
00:45:42,607 --> 00:45:44,540
Actually, it's very Santa fe,

626
00:45:44,609 --> 00:45:48,043
with the conflicting
earth tones
and the primitive motif.

627
00:45:48,112 --> 00:45:51,046
But the whole thing's
busy for me.

628
00:45:51,115 --> 00:45:53,349
How about you, Zeke?

629
00:45:53,417 --> 00:45:55,351
What does it mean,
Harlow?

630
00:45:55,419 --> 00:45:57,854
It's sort of
a signpost,

631
00:45:57,922 --> 00:46:00,857
a message to US
from the sioux.

632
00:46:00,925 --> 00:46:03,058
The message is,
uh, what?

633
00:46:03,127 --> 00:46:06,562
Well, it means if you can
read this message,

634
00:46:06,631 --> 00:46:09,398
you've come too far.

635
00:46:09,467 --> 00:46:11,400
I can't read.

636
00:46:11,469 --> 00:46:13,402
Where have you
led US?

637
00:46:13,471 --> 00:46:15,638
Oh, shut up, Ben.
Really!

638
00:46:15,707 --> 00:46:19,942
Harlow's instincts
were right. Following that
stupid map led US here.

639
00:46:20,011 --> 00:46:23,145
- Where is here?
- Indian country.

640
00:46:23,214 --> 00:46:25,781
- What?
- Indian country!

641
00:46:25,850 --> 00:46:30,285
Oh, great.
Just what we need.

642
00:46:30,354 --> 00:46:32,287
Oh!

643
00:46:32,356 --> 00:46:35,925
You got to
believe in him.

644
00:46:35,994 --> 00:46:39,896
Quiet down.
Quiet down!

645
00:46:39,964 --> 00:46:43,165
I said quiet--

646
00:46:43,234 --> 00:46:47,603
The man said
quiet down!

647
00:46:47,672 --> 00:46:51,574
- What the hell
was you thinking?
- I'm sorry.

648
00:46:51,643 --> 00:46:55,578
All right.
If we're going to survive
in Indian country,

649
00:46:55,647 --> 00:46:58,581
we're going to start
thinking like Indians.

650
00:46:58,650 --> 00:47:02,451
First, we'll walk barefoot,
just like the Indians.

651
00:47:02,520 --> 00:47:04,954
I thought Indians
wore moccasins.

652
00:47:05,023 --> 00:47:08,357
Well, Ben, we don't have
any moccasins.

653
00:47:08,426 --> 00:47:10,426
Excuse me,
gents.

654
00:47:10,494 --> 00:47:13,763
I actually
brought a pair
for summer wear.

655
00:47:13,831 --> 00:47:17,133
I really think
they'd just be perfect.

656
00:47:23,507 --> 00:47:25,708
Julian will wear moccasins,

657
00:47:25,776 --> 00:47:29,978
and the rest of US
will go barefoot.

658
00:47:37,521 --> 00:47:40,456
Next we'll wrap
all the metal riggings...

659
00:47:40,524 --> 00:47:42,458
On our horses and wagons--

660
00:47:42,526 --> 00:47:45,961
anything that rattles in cloth
to muffle the sound.

661
00:47:48,532 --> 00:47:51,967
We'll travel by night
and hide out by day.

662
00:47:52,035 --> 00:47:56,305
We'll make camp in an arroyo
so we're hidden from view.

663
00:47:56,374 --> 00:48:00,809
No campfires.
We'll sleep on the ground,
just like the Indians.

664
00:48:07,050 --> 00:48:11,420
I'm up. I'm up.
I'm up. I'm up.
I'm up. I'm up.

665
00:48:11,489 --> 00:48:13,489
What is it?

666
00:48:17,561 --> 00:48:19,561
Ahh.

667
00:48:26,069 --> 00:48:28,069
Ahh.

668
00:48:37,080 --> 00:48:39,080
Uh-oh.

669
00:49:16,620 --> 00:49:21,590
Uh... excuse me.

670
00:49:21,659 --> 00:49:24,593
Good morning!

671
00:49:24,662 --> 00:49:26,762
Uh, you speakum English?

672
00:49:56,694 --> 00:50:00,962
You've gotten US
in enough trouble.
I'll handle this.

673
00:50:11,542 --> 00:50:15,310
You want to shave
a buffalo butt...

674
00:50:15,379 --> 00:50:19,147
And dance naked
with a beaver?

675
00:50:19,216 --> 00:50:21,149
You speak English.
That's great.

676
00:50:21,218 --> 00:50:23,151
We want to travel east...

677
00:50:23,220 --> 00:50:25,888
To the land
of the rising sun.

678
00:50:25,956 --> 00:50:29,658
Skip the euphemisms.
I know which way east is.

679
00:50:29,727 --> 00:50:33,995
What did I do?

680
00:50:50,548 --> 00:50:54,650
Ha ha ha!

681
00:52:46,697 --> 00:52:49,130
I'd like you
to keep it...

682
00:52:49,199 --> 00:52:53,869
As a gift
from me to you
for your help.

683
00:52:58,609 --> 00:53:00,909
Wow! A Colt .45!

684
00:53:03,313 --> 00:53:06,048
Whoa!
Aah!

685
00:53:16,126 --> 00:53:19,360
Hyah! Head up!
head up!

686
00:54:00,004 --> 00:54:04,273
Damn! Oh!
Ow!

687
00:54:22,426 --> 00:54:28,030
Ah-ah-aah!

688
00:54:40,611 --> 00:54:44,480
Son of a bitch!

689
00:55:09,907 --> 00:55:12,007
Woo! Woo!

690
00:55:12,076 --> 00:55:14,076
Woo! Woo! Woo!

691
00:55:14,145 --> 00:55:16,078
Woo! Woo!
"More steam."

692
00:55:16,147 --> 00:55:18,680
"I thought I'd tell you.
We ain't got no more fuel.

693
00:55:18,749 --> 00:55:20,882
We run out of coal
two hours ago."

694
00:55:20,951 --> 00:55:24,920
"You what?"
"I was afraid of what
you'd do to me."

695
00:55:24,988 --> 00:55:29,624
"That's all right.
We'll demolish this church
and burn the wood."

696
00:55:29,693 --> 00:55:33,828
"No, please.
Whatever you do,
don't harm my church."

697
00:55:33,897 --> 00:55:37,533
"Shut up, preacher,
or I'll set your hat on fire.

698
00:55:37,601 --> 00:55:41,670
Ha ha ha!"
uh, sir.

699
00:55:41,738 --> 00:55:45,174
I told you
never to disturb me
at this hour!

700
00:55:45,242 --> 00:55:47,176
I am so sorry.

701
00:55:47,244 --> 00:55:50,679
We've been getting
some reports that some
of the homesteaders...

702
00:55:50,747 --> 00:55:54,516
Are having second thoughts
about the land rush.

703
00:55:54,585 --> 00:55:58,019
Apparently the word
about the wagon train
is spreading.

704
00:55:58,089 --> 00:56:00,456
What about
that wagon train, sir?

705
00:56:00,524 --> 00:56:02,924
Slade has not been
very effective.

706
00:56:02,993 --> 00:56:05,794
Fortunately,
I have a backup plan.

707
00:56:05,862 --> 00:56:07,796
Ahh!

708
00:56:07,864 --> 00:56:10,466
And they should be
just about there.

709
00:56:28,252 --> 00:56:31,186
So what brought you
out west, Julian?

710
00:56:31,255 --> 00:56:35,190
Oh, the men.
I just heard it was
chock-full of them.

711
00:56:35,259 --> 00:56:39,194
The men?
Oh, yeah. I get it.

712
00:56:39,263 --> 00:56:42,664
I guess men read more books
than women, right?
Y-Yes.

713
00:56:42,733 --> 00:56:44,833
Here you go,
Millie, darlin'.

714
00:56:49,406 --> 00:56:51,440
Ah, that's great.
Thanks.

715
00:56:53,511 --> 00:56:56,445
Hell.
Look at you, Julian.

716
00:56:56,514 --> 00:56:58,947
What did you see,
a mermaid?

717
00:56:59,016 --> 00:57:02,551
Cold water usually does
the opposite to me.

718
00:57:16,466 --> 00:57:19,400
Harlow, you've been
so good to me.

719
00:57:19,469 --> 00:57:23,271
Just doing
my job, ma'am.

720
00:57:23,340 --> 00:57:25,941
Listen...

721
00:57:26,009 --> 00:57:28,109
I was thinking.

722
00:57:28,178 --> 00:57:32,413
Maybe you'd like to come
to my wagon tonight,

723
00:57:32,482 --> 00:57:35,416
and we can talk...

724
00:57:35,485 --> 00:57:37,853
Or something.

725
00:57:42,492 --> 00:57:44,425
Ma'am, i--

726
00:57:45,996 --> 00:57:48,129
i'd--

727
00:57:48,198 --> 00:57:50,765
did I say
something wrong?

728
00:57:50,834 --> 00:57:53,969
No. No, ma'am.
You didn't say anything wrong.

729
00:57:54,037 --> 00:57:56,471
It's just that--
well, you see--

730
00:57:56,539 --> 00:57:59,975
fact is, I don't get paid
till St. Louis.

731
00:58:00,043 --> 00:58:03,578
As much as I'd like to,

732
00:58:03,646 --> 00:58:05,613
I just can't right now.

733
00:58:05,682 --> 00:58:08,116
But I will when I can...

734
00:58:08,185 --> 00:58:12,020
When I have
what I don't have now.
What?

735
00:58:12,089 --> 00:58:15,390
Well, I didn't mean--

736
00:58:15,458 --> 00:58:18,026
as if I'd consider it,

737
00:58:18,095 --> 00:58:20,528
you-- you...
You gimpy old drunk!

738
00:58:20,597 --> 00:58:23,932
Ma'am?
Ohh!

739
00:58:25,668 --> 00:58:28,703
Ohh!

740
00:58:30,974 --> 00:58:33,441
Hmph!

741
00:58:33,510 --> 00:58:35,510
Hyah! Hyah!

742
00:58:52,695 --> 00:58:55,931
Mount up!

743
00:58:55,999 --> 00:58:58,466
Wagons, ho!

744
00:58:58,535 --> 00:59:01,069
No, wait.
I'm Harlow.

745
00:59:01,138 --> 00:59:03,371
You were Harlow
last time.

746
00:59:03,440 --> 00:59:05,373
Hey, you know
something?

747
00:59:05,442 --> 00:59:07,375
Whatever we are
to the world,

748
00:59:07,444 --> 00:59:09,911
we're heroes to them.

749
00:59:09,980 --> 00:59:12,447
You can be Phil.
No way!

750
00:59:12,515 --> 00:59:15,951
I'd rather be
Harry Bob than Phil.

751
00:59:16,019 --> 00:59:19,955
Want to be
Harry Bob then?
okay.

752
00:59:20,023 --> 00:59:22,857
Let's go! Come on!

753
00:59:38,041 --> 00:59:41,476
Belle.
Harlow.

754
00:59:41,544 --> 00:59:44,980
I'd just like to apologize
for the other day.

755
00:59:45,048 --> 00:59:47,983
I don't know why--
oh, no. No. No.

